100000 rows 14 columns

Having downloaded each of the two datasets above, we see that they each contain 100k "jets" - corresponding to the jets created by a flux of particles from a collision of two proton beams. This is the data that will be used to analyze and search for the existence of the Higgs boson.

We can now plot many of the features of the data - and there are many, 14 in total - below to explore the data and describe what each of the parameters means. They are all related to a certain $p_T$ which is the transverse momentum of the particle collision. The reason this momentum is given as the transverse momentum and not just momentum is because the transverse momentum solely corresponds to the momentum of the newly created particle - the momentum perpendicular to the colliding beams. Any parallel component of the momentum is residual momentum from the proton-proton beam and is not interesting for our analysis purposes.

Let's explore our data.

fig, ax = plt.subplots(7, 2)
fig.tight_layout(pad=3.0)

for i in range(0,qcd.columns.size):
    name = qcd.columns[i]
    X1 = qcd[f'{name}']
    X2 = higgs[f'{name}']
    
    bins = 100
    
    row = math.floor(i/2)
    col = i%2
    
    ax[row, col].tick_params(labelsize = 15)
    ax[row, col].tick_params(labelsize = 15)
    ax[row, col].hist(X1, bins, color='r', linewidth = 3, label = 'qcd')
    ax[row, col].hist(X2, bins, color='g', alpha = 0.5, linewidth = 3, label='higgs')
    ax[row, col].set_title(f'{name}', fontsize = 15, fontweight='bold')
ax[0, 1].legend();

We have already described pt above, so we will begin introducing the other data variables.

First, we can see that 'phi' is really just the azimuthal angle about the axis of the colliding beams at which the detector detects the outcoming jets. The angle is seemingly random and is fairly evenly distributed across the values $-\pi<\phi<\pi$. Adding up all the collision counts across this space should yield the number of jets which is 100,000 as previously stated (this should be true for all other frames plotted above).

'Eta' is described as the pseudorapidity which is related to and depends on theta - the angle of the jet relative to the colliding beams. Thus, since the space in eta spans from negative infinity to infinity it makes sense that the distribution is a Gaussian centered on zero, as this will be the most probably value of eta. An eta of 0 corresponds to a jet with a completely perpendicular angle from the colliding beams (90 degrees) while an eta of specifically 1 and -1 corresponds to an angle of 40 and 130 degrees relative to the beam. Hence, eta of $\infty$ and $-\infty$ corresponds to jets parallel and antiparallel respectively to the beam. Hence, $-\infty < \eta < \infty$ corresponds to $-\pi < \theta < \pi$.

The mass is given in GeV and the most probable Higgs mass is stated as 125 GeV. This will of course have some uncertainty which is reflected in the Higgs dataset's mass data. The mass of the quantum chromodynamics (QCD) background particles are more spread out as the biproducts of pp-collisions can result in a variety of particles with different masses. The mass is reconstructed from the muon-corrected combined mass of the jet.

ee2 and ee3 correspond to the energies of (electromagnetic?) showers from for example the reactions $Z \rightarrow ee$.

The angularity seems to be related to phi and eta and possibly the difference between two beams symmetric about the beam axis.

t1, t2, t3, t21 and t32 are a little more ambiguous, but they all seem to have somewhat similar "hill-like" shapes and are related.

d2 - unknown

KtDeltaR - unknown

Discriminating between background (QCD) and data (Higgs)¶

We can also see that all variables, except phi, has clear discriminations between the background and the Higgs data. The reason phi does not discriminate between the noise and the background is because of the randomness of a transverse collision jet to travel in ANY direction perpendicular to the colliding beams (I have also talked about this previously but want to mention it here). It is purely random for both the background and the signal jets to travel in any direction between $-\pi$ and $\pi$ (corresponding to a full $2\pi$ rotation).

Correlations between features (not already previously mentioned)¶

Several of these properties are related to each other.

ee2 and ee3 have similar shapes and we plot them again with a smaller bin size to emphasize this.

Selection Plan¶

In order to detect a Higgs boson with some kind of confidence, we need to establish certain criteria for the experimental analysis that will be done in order to discover the Higgs boson.

Since the pseudorapidity eta is related to how perpendicular the jet is relative to the beam and thus how much the jet is independent of the incidents beams (only contains momentum of particles created in the collision) - this is a natural selection criteria. Therefore, we should plan to select jets with eta close to 0. The most transverse jets are the ones we are interested in.

Moreover, another selection criteria for our experiment must be some sort of high $p_T$. This is because the jet must contain at least some threshold of created particles and thus transverse momentum. We need some criteria for a high p_T.
